# {{lb|en|philosophy|theology}} [[divine#Adjective|Divine]] [[providence]], [[foreknowledge]], [[foresight]].
#* {{quote-book|author=Walter Raleigh|authorlink=Walter Raleigh|chapter=Of the Creation, and Preservation of the World|title=The Historie of the World. In Five Bookes.{{nb...|1 Intreating of the Beginning and First Ages of the Same, from the Creation unto Abraham. 2 Of the Times from the Birth of Abraham, to the Destruction of the Temple of Salomon. 3 From the Destruction of Jerusalem, to the Time of Philip of Macedon. 4 From the Reigne of Philip of Macedon, to the Establishing of that Kingdome, in the Race of Antigonus. 5 From the Settled Rule of Alexanders Successors in the East, untill the Romans (Prevailing over All) Made Conquest of Asia and Macedon.}}|location=London|publisher=Printed for [[w:Walter Burre|Walter Bvrre]]|year=1614|section=§&nbsp;XIII (Of Providence)|page=15|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=JcZMAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA15|oclc=505085272|passage=Now Providence (which the ''Greekes'' call '''''Pronoia''''') is an intellectuall knowledge, both fore-ſeeing, caring for, and ordering all things, and doth not onely behold all paſt, all present, and all to come, but is the cauſe of their ſo being, which Preſcience (ſimply taken) is not: and therefore Providence by the Philoſophers (ſaith [[w:Augustine of Hippo|S. ''Auguſtine'']]) is divided into Memory, Knowledge, and Care: {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Thomas Chalmers|authorlink=Thomas Chalmers|chapter=Lecture XCIV: Romans, xiii, 11–14|title=Lectures on the Epistle of Paul the Apostle to the Romans|series=The Works of Thomas Chalmers|seriesvolume=25|volume=IV|location=Glasgow|publisher=[[w:William Collins (publisher)|William Collins]],{{nb...|S. Frederick St.}}; London: Hamilton, Adams, & Co.|year=1836–1842|pages=320–321|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=r7dDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA321|oclc=606228745|passage=&#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=r7dDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA320 page 320]&#93; 'And make no provision for the flesh.' [Romans 13:14] 'Provision.' [''footnote'': {{lang|grc|Προνοια}}.] The word implies a forecasting of the mind; and the prohibition therefore is against all deliberation or devising of means or expedients for the gratification of our lusts. {{...}} &#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=r7dDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA321 page 321]&#93; He is a confirmed and advanced learner in the school of wickedness, who can thus in his cooler moments bestow care and calculation on such an enterprise, and in short make a study of the likeliest methods for securing to himself te enjoyment of unhallowed pleasures; and this is the '''''pronoia''''', the unholy ''providence'', if it may be so termed, on which our text lays its interdict. But it is not against all '''''pronoia''''', all respect to things future, even though the futurities of this life, that the Bible warns us.}}
#* {{quote-journal|author=E. E. Higbee|title=Art IV.—The Christian Conception of History.|editor=T. G. Apple|journal=The Mercersburg Review; an Organ for Christological, Historical and Positive Theology|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher=[[w:Reformed Church in the United States|Reformed Church Publication Board]],{{nb...|54 N. Sixth Street}}|month=January|year=1869|volume=XVI|page=101|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mP0QAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA101|oclc=610823203|passage=The development of the Roman State, therefore, a world-process whose magnitude is truly wonderful, was not brought about as though a drifting mass of elements, by some outward force or inherent affinity became consolidated to revolve at random without any end or aim in that divine '''''pronoia''''' under which the ages move.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=F[rancis] E[dward] Peters|authorlink=Francis Edward Peters|chapter=prónoia: ''forethought'', ''providence''|title=Greek Philosophical Terms: A Historical Lexicon|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|New York University Press}}|year=1967|section=paragraph 1|page=164|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=JepR6Mj9Hy8C&pg=PA164|oclc=802943168|passage=The earlier history of the concept of providence is to be seen in the emergence, from {{w|Diogenes}} to {{w|Aristotle}}, of a notion of an intelligent purpose (''telos'', q.v.) operating in the universe. In all of these thinker it is clearly associated with the intelligent God whose features begin to appear in the later {{w|Plato}} (see ''Laws'' 899 where the denial of '''''pronoia''''' is reckoned blasphemy) and in Aristotle. For the Stoics the immanent ''Logos'' governs all by ''nous and '''pronoia''''' (D.L. {{smallcaps|vii}}, 138; ''SVF'' {{smallcaps|i}}, 176).}}
# {{lb|en|historical|Byzantine Empire}} An [[imperial]] [[grant#Noun|grant]] to an individual of [[temporary]] [[fiscal]] [[right#Noun|rights]] in the form of [[land#Noun|land]], [[income]]s or [[tax#Noun|taxes]] from land, [[fishing#Noun|fishing]] rights, etc., sometimes carrying with it an [[obligation]] of [[military]] [[service#Noun|service]].
#* {{quote-book|author=Mark C. Bartusis|chapter=Smallholding and Pronoia Soldiers and Their Financing|editor={{w|Ruth Mazo Karras}}|title=The Late Byzantine Army: Arms and Society, 1204–1453|series=The Middle Ages Series|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher={{w|University of Pennsylvania Press}}|year=1992|section=part 2 (The Army as Institution)|page=183|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rUs-hHd89xAC&pg=PA183|isbn=978-0-8122-1620-2|passage=Unlike fiefs, '''pronoiai''' were granted only by the emperor, and so they played no role in producing the subinfeudation and the hierarchical social and political structure characteristic of Western feudalism. '''Pronoia''' was a fiscal and administrative institution; the fief territorial and personal. The grant of a '''pronoia''' was primarily a grant of revenue expressed as a monetary sum (the posotes), not in terms of a quantity of property.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=John V[an] A[ntwerp] Fine, Jr.|authorlink=John Van Antwerp Fine Jr.|chapter=The Second Half of the Thirteenth Century|title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest|location=Ann Arbor, Mich.|publisher={{w|University of Michigan Press}}|year=1987|page=170|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvVbRrH1QBgC&pg=PA170|isbn=978-0-472-10079-8|passage=By 1270 [[w:Michael VIII Palaiologos|Michael VIII]] had issued charters to two monasteries in eastern Thessaly near the Gulf of Volos (Makrinitisa and Neopetra), showing he had acquired that region. From these years imperial grants of '''pronoias''' and of tax exemptions to various notables of east Thessaly begin appearing. Thus probably in 1267/68 the Byzantines regained some or all of Thessaly's east coast.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Nicolas Oikonomides|authorlink=Nicolas Oikonomides|author2=John Solman, transl.|chapter=The Role of the Byzantine State in the Economy|editor=[[w:Angeliki Laiou|Angeliki E. Laiou]]|title=The Economic History of Byzantium: From the Seventh through the Fifteenth Century|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:Dunbarton Oaks|Dunbarton Oaks Research Library and Collection]]|year=2002|volume=3|section=part 5 (Economic Institutions and the State)|pages=1045–1046|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Igp8hxsHV_AC&pg=PA1045|isbn=978-0-88402-288-6|passage=The economic composition of the '''''pronoia''''' belonging to a heavy cavalryman in the fourteenth century, such as those who served in the ''mega allagion'' (regiment) of Thessalonike in the fourteenth century, is known to us from some of the ''praktika'' of '''''pronoia''''' holders that have survived. {{...}} According to the ''praktikon'', the revenue of the ''pronoiarios'' consisted of two parts. The first was the ''oikoumenon'', that is, the sum of all the personal taxes paid to the '''''pronoia''''' holder by his ''paroikoi'' resident on the '''''pronoia''''', depending on the means of production at the disposal of each ''paroikos''. {{...}} The second part consisted of secondary taxes and rights (e.g., on fishing, the ''ennomion'', and the tax on flax-retting units), but above all of land, on which, theoretically, the full tax was payable{{nb...}}.}}

