===Etymology 2===
{{prefix|en|pro|paranoia|alt2=(para)noia}}, coined by American sociologist Fred H. Goldner in a paper presented at the annual meeting of the {{w|Society for the Study of Social Problems}} in August 1981. A version of this paper, entitled “Pronoia”, was published in the journal ''Social Problems'' in October 1982: see the quotation.<ref>{{R:OED Online|part of speech=''n.{{sup|2}}''|noformat=yes|id=265077|date=June 2007}}</ref>

====Noun====
{{en-noun|?}}

# {{lb|en|psychology}} A [[belief]] (sometimes regarded as [[irrational#Adjective|irrational]]) that [[person|people]] [[conspire]] to do one [[good]]. {{defdate|from 1981}}
#: {{antonyms|en|paranoia}}
#* {{quote-journal|author=Fred H. Goldner|title=Pronoia|journal={{w|Social Problems}}|location=Berkeley, Calif.|publisher=Published by the {{w|University of California Press}} for the {{w|Society for the Study of Social Problems}}|date=1 October 1982|volume=30|issue=1|section=abstract|page=82|doi=10.2307/800186|issn=	0037-7791|oclc=1667861|passage='''Pronoia''' is the positive counterpart of paranoia. It is the delusion that others think well of one. Actions and the products of one's efforts are thought to be well received and praised by others. Mere acquaintances are thought to be close friends; politeness and the exchange of pleasantries are taken as expressions of deep attachment and the promise of future support. '''Pronoia''' appears to be rooted in the social complexity and cultural ambiguity of our lives: we have become increasingly dependent on the opinions of others based on uncertain criteria.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Trudy Govier|authorlink=Trudy Govier|chapter={{w|Socrates}}, the Sting Ray of Athens|title=Socrates’ Children: Thinking and Knowing in the Western Tradition|location=Peterborough, Ont.; Orchard Park, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Broadview Press}}|year=1997|page=18|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=5i_fBCYPoY4C&pg=PA18|isbn=978-1-55111-093-6|passage="'''Pronoia'''" is comparable to paranoia (which is commonly believed to be a mental disease), but is its emotional opposite. The paranoic thinks that everyone and everything are conspiring against him. So-called pronoids see reality as quite positive, and regard themselves as responsible for good things, which they are convinced are going to happen. If paranoia is a mental disorder, then '''pronoia''' is a mental disorder. So (apparently) happiness is a mental disorder.}}

